Ill use 3 main packages:

  • ggplot2

Linear regression

Fit a linear model:

# data from hw2
courtpenalties <- read_dta("data/courtpenalties2020_compatible.dta")

f1 <- penalties ~ minority + liberal + popsize + crt + unemp
model1 <- glm(f1, family = gaussian(), data = courtpenalties)
summary(model1)

augment(model1) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = crt, y = .resid)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Inspect residuals for heteroskedasticity")

Coefficient plots

Coefficient plots are an alternative to looking at tables of coefficients.

model1_df <- tidy(model1, conf.int = TRUE, conf.level = .95) 

model1_df %>%
  filter(term != "(Intercept)") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = fct_rev(term), y = estimate)) + 
  geom_pointrange(aes(ymin = conf.low, ymax = conf.high)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed") +
  coord_flip() + 
  labs(title = "Model 1: linear regression", 
       subtitle = "Estimated coefficient + 95% CI",
       x = NULL, 
       y = "coefficient")

These arent standardized, so the scales are really different.

Note: ggstance::geom_pointrangeh() also gives a horizontal version of geom_pointrange(). I felt like I was already using enough packages, though

Marginal effects plots

Instead of plotting coefficients, we can use those coefficients to get predictions on the y scale at different x values. In particular, we can plot specific counterfactual values of x.

This is something we could do manually using the predict() function, but doing those calculations can be tricky with GLMs. (Its relatively easy with lm().)

Instead, well use the ggeffects package. The margins package, which is based off of a Stata command, does something similar.

There are two ways of showing uncertainty in these plots:

  • through the confidence intervals of the conditional means. This incorporates the uncertainty in the systematic part of the modelthe estimates of your coefficients.
  • through the prediction intervals of the data. This incorporates both the systematic uncertainty from the coefficients, and the uncertainty from the stochastic part of the model.

First, well pick one covariate, crt. By default, ggpredict holds the other continuous variables constant at their mean (and categorical variables at their reference values).

ggpredict(model1, terms = "crt")
## 
## # Predicted values of avg $ assessed
## # x = crime rate (per 1000)
## 
##   x predicted std.error conf.low conf.high
##   0  3036.884    81.396 2877.350  3196.418
##  10  3532.305    53.290 3427.859  3636.752
##  20  4027.727    31.015 3966.939  4088.515
##  30  4523.149    31.492 4461.426  4584.872
##  40  5018.571    54.122 4912.493  5124.648
##  50  5513.992    82.307 5352.674  5675.310
##  60  6009.414   111.925 5790.045  6228.783
## 
## Adjusted for:
## * minority =   929.17
## *  liberal =    37.83
## *  popsize = 23770.58
## *    unemp =    10.27
ggpredict(model1, terms = "crt", interval = "confidence", ci.level = .95) %>%
  plot() +
  labs(subtitle = "95% confidence interval")

ggpredict(model1, terms = "crt", interval = "prediction", ci.lvl = .95) %>% 
  plot() +
  labs(subtitle = "95% prediction interval")

Interaction terms

Thats a simple association. Lets a second model, adding an interaction term:

f2 <- update(f1, ~ . + crt*minority)
model2 <- glm(f2, family = gaussian(), data = courtpenalties)
tidy(model2)
## # A tibble: 7 x 5
##   term         estimate std.error statistic  p.value
##   <chr>           <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)  224.     241.          0.929 3.53e- 1
## 2 minority       0.678    0.121       5.61  3.66e- 8
## 3 liberal        2.14     4.38        0.489 6.25e- 1
## 4 popsize        0.0837   0.00507    16.5   6.60e-48
## 5 crt            7.36     5.14        1.43  1.53e- 1
## 6 unemp          4.49     5.38        0.834 4.05e- 1
## 7 minority:crt   0.0434   0.00443     9.79  1.32e-20

Now the association between crt and penalties depends on the size of the non-white population. Lets pick 3 values of minority for our plot.

model2_predictions <- ggpredict(model2, terms = c("crt", "minority [meansd]")) 

plot(model2_predictions) + theme(legend.position = "bottom")

Again, with prediction intervals instead:

ggpredict(model2, 
          terms = c("crt", "minority [meansd]"), 
          interval = "prediction") %>% 
  plot() + 
  labs(subtitle = "At mean non-white pop  1sd, 95% prediction interval") +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

Logistic regression

grants <- read_csv("data/fedgrants&researchclimate.csv")
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   hidegree = col_double(),
##   budget = col_double(),
##   climate = col_double(),
##   ehoursx = col_double(),
##   researchx = col_double(),
##   id = col_double(),
##   state = col_double(),
##   fedgrants = col_double(),
##   mandate = col_double(),
##   researchdiv = col_double()
## )
grants <- 
  grants %>%
  mutate(grant = ifelse(fedgrants > 0, 1, 0))

model3 <- glm(grant ~ hidegree + budget + climate, 
              family = binomial(link = "logit"),
              data = grants)

ggpredict(model3, terms = "budget [all]", interval = "confidence") %>% plot()

ggpredict(model3, terms = "budget [all]", interval = "prediction") %>% plot()
